04377nam a22006735i 9780226695310DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020021304  a9780226695310  a(DE-B1597)571672  a(OCoLC)1206394346  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aBF381b.L66 2020 4aBF381 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a153.1/41 aLong, Seth, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aExcavating the Memory Palace :bArts of Visualization from the Agora to the Computer /cSeth Long. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b20 halftones, 12 line drawings  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Memory vs. Mnemonic -- tChapter 1. Arts of Memory in the Agora -- tChapter 2. Arts of Memory in the Monastery -- tChapter 3. The Memory Palace in Ruins -- tChapter 4. The Memory Palace Modernized -- tChapter 5. Theory and Practice of a Digital Ars Memoria -- tChapter 6. The Social Memory Palace -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWith the prevalence of smartphones, massive data storage, and search engines, we might think of today as the height of the information age. In reality, every era has faced its own challenges of storing, organizing, and accessing information. While they lacked digital devices, our ancestors, when faced with information overload, utilized some of the same techniques that underlie our modern interfaces: they visualized and spatialized data, tying it to the emotional and sensory spaces of memory, thereby turning their minds into a visual interface for accessing information. In Excavating the Memory Palace, Seth David Long mines the history of Europe’s arts of memory to find the origins of today’s data visualizations, unearthing how ancient constructions of cognitive pathways paved the way for modern technological interfaces. Looking to techniques like the memory palace, he finds the ways that information has been tied to sensory and visual experience, turning raw data into lucid knowledge. From the icons of smart phone screens to massive network graphs, Long shows us the ancestry of the cyberscape and unveils the history of memory as a creative act.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aMemory. 0aMnemonicsxHistory. 0aMnemonics-History. 0aMnemonics. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  adigital humanities.  amemory.  anew media.  arhetoric.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069309640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226695310423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226695310/original  a978-3-11-069309-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-6  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishb2020  a978-3-11-070473-0  EBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-DEGb2020  aZDB-23-DGGb2020